Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** (from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`) to host your server in-process, then point an MCP client at it via the factory's `CreateClient()` HTTP client.

### Key pattern

```csharp
// 1. Create the in-memory test server
await using var factory = new WebApplicationFactory<Program>();
var httpClient = factory.CreateClient();

// 2. Connect an MCP client through it
var transport = new SseClientTransport(
    new SseClientTransportOptions
    {
        Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/sse"),
        Name = "test-client"
    },
    httpClient);            // ← passes the factory-backed HttpClient

await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

// 3. Test real MCP operations
var tools = await mcpClient.ListToolsAsync();
Assert.NotEmpty(tools);

var result = await mcpClient.CallToolAsync("my-tool", new { input = "hello" });
Assert.Equal("expected", result.Content[0].Text);
```

### What makes this work

| Piece | Role |
|---|---|
| `WebApplicationFactory<Program>` | Hosts your full ASP.NET Core pipeline (middleware, DI, routing) in-memory — no ports, no real network. |
| `factory.CreateClient()` | Returns an `HttpClient` whose handler short-circuits to the in-memory server. |
| `SseClientTransport` / `StreamableHttpClientTransport` | The MCP C# SDK transports accept an `HttpClient`, so they use the factory-backed one transparently. |

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol  # MCP C# SDK
```

> **Tip:** If your server uses Streamable HTTP instead of SSE, swap `SseClientTransport` for `StreamableHttpClientTransport` with the same `httpClient` injection pattern.

This gives you full protocol-level coverage (initialization, tool calls, resources, prompts) with fast, deterministic, no-network tests.
